defaultAssociation of British Insurers – Written evidencedefault&#xa0;defaultThe ABI is the voice of insurance, representing the general insurance, protection, investment and long-term savings industry.  It was formed in 1985 to represent the whole of the industry and today has over 300 members, accounting for some 90% of premiums in the UK.
default&#xa0;
defaultDraft Deregulation Billdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe ABI supports the overall aim of the Draft Deregulation Bill 
defaultto remove unnecessary
defaultbureaucracy that costs British businesses and hinders individuals in their daily lives. However, we would have concerns about specific areas of the Bill that would benefit from additional consideration.
default&#xa0;
defaultSCHEDULE 3 defaultMOTOR INSURANCE INDUSTRY: CERTIFICATES OF INSURANCEdefault&#xa0;defaultThe consequences of these changes would be to continue to allow insurers to issue certificates, but that the surrender of the certificate by the consumer upon cancellation of the policy would no longer to be necessary. This change would therefore abolish the offence of not returning a certificate upon cancellation of a motor insurance policy.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ABI estimates that this change would save around 6 million people a year having to return their certificates. Many of those who fail to return their motor insurance certificates are currently in breach of the law but enforcement is almost non-existent. 
defaultWe estimate that by using the Motor Insurance Database as evidence of cancellation the overall cost saving to the industry will be in the region of £45 million.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of this would be for more claims to fall on the Motor Insurance Bureau (MIB) and fewer on insurers directly, but the gross level of claims would be unaltered and, so, motor insurance costs would remain unchanged. The MIB would determine how the additional cost of claims would be allocated between its members.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do not think the Bill, written in its current format, is clear on where policy restrictions can be put and we have outlined our proposed amends below.
